# Compare calorie per workout

def calorie_stats(data):
    min_calories = round(min(data.calories), 4)
    max_calories = round(max(data.calories), 4)
    mean_calories = round(np.mean(data.calories), 4)
    median_calories = round(stats.median(data.calories), 4)
    mode_calories = round(stats.mode(data.calories), 4)
    calories_std = round(np.std(data.calories), 4)
    calories_var = round(np.var(data.calories), 4)
    return f"""Workout Type: {max(data.workout_type)}
Minimum Calories: {min_calories}
Maximum Calories: {max_calories}
Mean Calories: {mean_calories}
Median Calories: {median_calories}
Mode Calories: {mode_calories}
Calorie Standard Deviation: {calories_std}
Calorie Variance: {calories_var}
"""

We can see from the data that open water swimming had the highest total calories burnt but cricket had the highest mean of calories burnt. This leads me to infer that the user prefers to play cricket and may be playing it at a higher level or for a longer time. We can calculate this and get a more definitive answer.

In [141]:
def time_stats(data):   
    min_time = round(min(data.time), 4)
    max_time = round(max(data.time), 4)
    mean_time = round(np.mean(data.time), 4)
    median_time = round(stats.median(data.time), 4)
    mode_time = round(stats.mode(data.time), 4)
    time_std = round(np.std(data.time), 4)
    time_var = round(np.var(data.time), 4)
    return f"""Workout Type: {max(data.workout_type)}
Minimum time: {min_time}
Maximum time: {max_time}
Mean time: {mean_time}
Median time: {median_time}
Mode time: {mode_time}
Time Standard Deviation: {time_std}
Time Variance: {time_var}
"""
